{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488299"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:36:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"406"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/406"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.21,0.15,0.57,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102329"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/406"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"406"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4228"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6472"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35166"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42076"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102329"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 82-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for advice about a lesion on his face. This has been present for about eight years and has not shown any obvious change; however, the patient\u0027s son encouraged him to seek medical advice. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lesion is a 2 cm irregularly pigmented macule with indistinct borders on his left cheek.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal cell carcinoma","Solar keratosis","Seborrhoeic keratosis","Lentigo maligna","Nodular melanoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the high prevalence of skin cancer in Australia, it is important for skin lesions to be assessed and monitored for change. Charts and dermoscopic photographs assist in this process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELentigo maligna\u003C/strong\u003E may be present for many months or years prior to local invasion occurring. This is consistent with the eight-year history given by the patient. These typically occur on the head and neck of elderly patients and are associated with chronic sun exposure. Lentigo maligna is considered to be a subtype of melanoma-in-situ with a lower risk of transition to invasive melanoma. Once it invades the dermis, it is classified as lentigo maligna melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrhoeic keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E may appear similar to these lesions; however, they are typically more well-demarcated and often raised with a \u0027stuck-on\u0027 appearance. There are flat pigmented seborrhoeic keratoses, and distinguishing these from lentigo maligna can be challenging without dermoscopy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENodular melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E lesions are often elevated, firm and growing. They tend to have more rapid vertical growth and therefore appear thick at diagnosis. The long-standing nature of this lesion without obvious change makes nodular melanoma unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinomas\u003C/strong\u003E typically have a characteristic appearance with a rolled edge and a \u0027pearly\u0027 appearance. They may also have overlying telangiectasia. The described irregularly pigmented macule with indistinct borders is not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESolar keratosis\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most common skin lesions and arises due to sun damage. They typically appear as red, flat and scaly lesions rather than pigmented macules. They are precursors to squamous cell carcinoma rather than melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lentigo maligna is a subtype of melanoma-in-situ that typically occurs on sun-exposed areas of elderly patients and may be present for years before invasion.","Lentigo maligna appears as an irregularly pigmented macule with indistinct borders, commonly on the face or neck.","Distinguishing lentigo maligna from other pigmented lesions requires careful assessment of clinical features and often dermoscopy or biopsy."],"references":["Clinical practice guidelines for the diagnosis and management of melanoma. In: Cancer Council Australia Clinical Practice Guidelines [online]. Available at: https://www.cancer.org.au/clinical-guidelines/skin-cancer/melanoma","Sinclair R. Skin checks. Aust J Gen Practitioners. 2012;41:464-9. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/july/skin-checks"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"406"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15909"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15909"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8e80a901-06da-4f25-ab78-45bf76e943e0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8e80a901-06da-4f25-ab78-45bf76e943e0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"he